            <section class="full">
                <div>
                    <p><strong>Heritage Recipe: Macaroni and Cheese</strong></p>
                    <p>From the Kitchen of Laura and Bo Duncan</p>
                    <p>William and Laura Duncan Duncan moved to the big white house with the wraparound porch at 436 Oxford Road in 1951. World War II Navy veteran William Duncan had been hired as a civil engineer for the S. B. Church Company after Mr. Church died. Laura, a gradu- ate of Amherst College, had worked in a laboratory in Boston developing latex paint before her marriage. The house was home to the couple’s three girls: Terry, Toni and Elizabeth or Bo as she was known, and their brothers Pete and Jim.</p>
                    <p>The house was in need of many repairs, but located in a wonderful neighborhood for children. The Duncan clan played outside all day long with the Hessler, Crepeau, Schade and DeMaio families. “Our parents let us be kids which was really nice,” says Bo. The backyard was planted with a large stand of pine trees and Pete and Jim and their friends quickly learned to leap from one to another. Laura headed upstairs and pretended she didn’t know what was going on until the day when Jim grabbed a branch with a hornet’s nest. His multiple stings were treated with the family cure all of a bathtub filled with water and Epsom salts. "You can’t cry in the bathtub," Laura told them all.</p>
                    <figure>
                        <img src="/resources/graphics/newletters/2023.01/436-oxford-road.jpg" alt="436 Oxford Road">
                        <figcaption>436 Oxford Road</figcaption>
                    </figure>
                    <p>In his free time, William Duncan undertook renovating his home. At one time anyone opening the door could look straight down into the cellar. Old walls came down, and a pile of ancient lathe provided kindling for the evening fire in the fireplace. While preparing to paper the dining room one Valentine’s Day, he drew a big heart on the wall that he emblazoned “Laura and Bill.” When Bo built her own home on Great Hill Road, she repeated the tradition on her first Christmas there, painting trees to decorate her new house. They are now covered with paint, but still there in her memory each holiday season. He also created a beautiful yard that ran back to Jack’s Brook for his family. Challenged by all the rocks when he wanted a driveway, he enlisted the children to load them into a trailer. Anyone who helped got to drive the tractor to dump them. Fall brought them all out to rake and pile leaves in the back of an S. B. Church truck in return for a ride to the compost heap.</p>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <p>Bo relates that Thursday night the Duncans often had macaroni and cheese for supper. This was because Thursday was piano lesson day. “My two brothers and I each had a half hour lesson after school. While we were all doing that Mom would go grocery shopping but this left no time to make supper once we got home. Macaroni and cheese could be prepared and left in the oven to bake while we were away. Once we got home, out of the oven it came and supper was on the table.” Laura Duncan’s recipe, derived from her Fanny Farmer Cookbook, follows.</p>
                    <figure>
                        <img src="/resources/graphics/newletters/2023.01/mac-and-cheese.jpg" alt="The Duncan Family’s Macaroni & Cheese">
                        <figcaption>The Duncan Family’s Macaroni & Cheese</figcaption>
                    </figure>
                    <p><strong>The Duncan Family’s Macaroni & Cheese</strong>
                    <p>First make the cream sauce: in a double boiler or heavy saucepan, melt 4 tablespoons of butter. Add 4 tablespoons of flour and blend well over low heat. Add to this 2 cups of milk or milk and cream. Whisk the sauce and bring it slowly to a boil. Cook for 2 minutes stirring constantly. Season with salt and pepper.</p>
                    <p>Now to make the Macaroni and Cheese:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Cook a 9 oz. package of macaroni according to pack age directions.</li>
                        <li>Put half in a buttered baking dish. Sprinkle it with 1/2 cup of cheddar cheese (or more)</li>
                        <li>Add the rest of the macaroni. Sprinkle another 1/2 cup of cheddar cheese (or more) on top.</li>
                        <li>Pour in the 2 cups of cream sauce.</li>
                        <li>Put 1/2 cup of buttered bread crumbs on top.</li>
                        <li>Bake at 400 degrees until brown, 25 – 30 minutes.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>If you are going to piano lessons then cook until you get home but at a lower temperature.</p>
                    
                </div>
